text:
Loved this place so much that we came here three times during our week long trip in New Orleans. Tried the following:

Fried alligator - flavorful sauce, the meat tasted something between fish and chicken;

Paneed pork cheeks - okay, not too impressed;

Gulf shrimp with fermented black bean sauce - fresh and flavorful, one of our favorites;

Wood fired eggplant - simple with olive oil, salt and lemon juice, but cooked to perfect tenderness;

Shrimp and eggplant dressing - my favorite and ordered it every time;

Smoked pork ribs with watermelon pickle - the ribs were a little dry, but the sauce was rich and the watermelon pickle was a nice touch;

Fried boudin - first time had boudin, interesting but won't order again;

Louisiana cochon - supposed to be their signature dish, the veggies tasted like Russian Borscht, and the cracklins were too hard for my teeth; a bit disappointed but maybe I expected too much;

Wood fired oysters - best grilled oysters hands down! Don't even bother with Acme's overly cheesy grilled oysters. These oysters are to die for!

Even bought chef Donald Link's Real Cajun cookbook especially for the recipes of wood fired oysters and shrimp & eggplant dressing!

Set in a renovated warehouse in the Lower Garden District, Cochon is one of the most hipster restaurants around town. Although it might be intimidating to some that the members of the waitstaff are covered in tattoos/piercings, they are super friendly and down to earth. The interior design is rustic, industrial chic, somewhat reminiscent of Portland.

I recommend visiting Cochon in a large group and ordering tapas style. In fact, my biggest regret of the evening was not being able to try out more items on the menu! All the dishes we ordered fit the bill of authentic Cajun Southern.

// wood-fired oysters with chili garlic butter ($14) - 5 stars
These were my favorite oysters from the entire NOLA trip. That's saying a lot, considering how many we sampled across different restaurants. So good that we had two orders.

// fried alligator with chili garlic mayonnaise ($12) - 4 stars
A tad salty, but the spiciness of the mayonnaise balanced it out. Have the alligator, mint, and onions all in one bite.

// louisiana cochon with cabbage, crackline & pickled peaches ($24) - 5 stars
It would be sacrilegious to dine at a restaurant named after food without tasting the namesake dish! The cochon was sweet and I enjoyed the addition of the chicharrones on top.

// beef short rib with tomato, squash, pickled okra & slow roasted grits ($27) - 5 stars
Really tender beef short rib. The peppers added some good texture to the grits.

// macaroni & cheese casserole ($7) - 3 stars
Very creamy, but otherwise ordinary.
